JJ_GaryMay24

By Gary

Pear Note Website



  1. Let’s talk a bit about you - can you talk to me a bit about what you do?
  2. [JJ] I am a patient technology coordinator. Its a very unique role, pretty much to this hospital. There are other hospitals that have similar titles or positions that have kind of been modeled or inspired by kind of what my role was in the past. I’m in a more administrator role now. I used to be more hands on, and on the floor providing technology based education recreational interventions with patients and families. I’m a certified child life specialist and certified recreation therapist by training. What i was doing in the past, and probably what you’ll hear from the others you speak to, with roles similar to mine, is that i was basically working with therapists to identify ways to incorporate technology that was both recreational and educational into their therapeutic processes. So like bringing video games into a physical therapy session, or VR into a child life intervention. Or helping teachers understand how to use skype or like twitch, and minecraft into their lesson plan. 
  3. [JJ] My current role is a bit different now. Now i oversee programming for all these things. It grew very rapidly so now my most of job is talking to people like your. And talking to charities, organizations, and both volunteer, for profit and non profit. Anybody whose interested in bringing that technology into our hospital and then I try to create some programming around it to support that in a meaningful manner. So I’m kind of like the gatekeeper for all of that technology that is coming into the hospital. Then I oversee people who now do the job that I used to do. Its mostly volunteers, some are contractors. And some others are - I’m actually in the process of creating 2 full time positions to replace myself in that clinical role. I was working everyday on the floor with patients and families. 
  4. [Gary] So do you have more hands on time time with patients in your current role or in the previous one?
  5. [JJ]  In my former role I had a lot more hands on time with them. Now I’m very little hands on with the patients, except for major events, or I were rolling out a new program. I would be on the floor much more to make sure the program was running smooth. I would shadow people who were bringing the program out. I would interact with the patients more but for about the last year now I’ve been overseeing the people who are having the more hands on approach. So I think like andrew reached out to Shreya yesterday. He is contracted out through GameStart school, he has a much more hands on time with the patient. He spends every single day working with patients.  He’s kinda of replaced my role there.



[GD] Can you briefly describe your hospital

  1. [JJ] We’re a level 1 Trauma children’s hospital. That means we take some of the most severe cases in the world. We have 250 ish beds, it kind of changes on what constructions going on. Those are all in patient. We also have an emergency department, we have a surgery area that sees about 100 - 300 a day. And we have a number of outpatient clinics as well. All of our rooms are single bed. They all have their own bathroom, own TV. Almost every unit has an activity room for the kids to play in. 


  3. [GD] How many patients does your role impact?
  4. [JJ] All of them. The technology that goes into the rooms for instance, the first big project I took on - is we have an xbox 360 in every patients room. I help oversee the process of putting Xboxes in. I actually ran the pilot program. And that was when I was actually working as a clinician where I was troubleshooting and figuring out how that works with the patients. Many of our Xbox were online so I helped troubleshoot those issues as well. I work very closely with the IT dept. All of the programming that I developed which includes bedside VR for our patients. Bedside LEGO robotic for our patients. Also bedside videogame interaction with our patients were created by me and overseen by me. We are currently working on livestreaming events and so I’m taking a heavy hand in that. And also the (unintelligible) ZOTT pilot was pretty much me overseeing that and trying to train how to utilize that. We have a few other programs that I oversee that affect our clinics and affect our patients once they leave the hospital. 


  6. [GD] What do the staffing numbers look like? - the number of people who work with the technology and the kids on the floor
  7. [JJ] For CLS we typically have one CLS  - So each one of our units is 32 beds. We have 2 units per floor. There is 1 CLS per unit. There is 1 activity therapist - which is the person who runs the playroom per floor. And as far as support on the technology side on my end who I oversee - currently we contract 1 person to do all the bedside VR, thats through gamestart school, and thats going to be running out pretty soon, and that will be replaced pretty soon with a patient technologist. (is contract technologist Andrew?). And I have sporadic volunteers who come and provide regular videogame entertainment for the kids, they deliver games to the kids, and help troubleshoot the xbox 360s. And then I have a gentleman who does LEGO bedside engineering with the kids - hes there 20 hours a week. And Then I have a temp who is currently helping all all the child life staff with all their IPAD issues - he’s updated their ipads, getting new ones, and troubleshooting anything thats IOS related. 


  9. [GD] Can you walk me through what a typical day looks like in your current role. And then walk me through what a day looked like in your old role. I’m interested in understanding what a day on the floor looks like.  
  10. [JJ] My current role its not too exciting to shadow me. Its meetings. It’s typically answering a bunch of emails in the morning, and having various meetings with groups like ZOTT, gamechangers, childsplay, or also meeting with child life staff CLS. I try to meet with them every morning, they have a huddle in the morning and I try to attend those - its their way of touching base with everybody. And so I go there to see if they’re having any issues with the technology running throughout the hospital. I also send out emails to all the child life staff CLS to ask them to provide me with room numbers and ages of patients who my VR and LEGO people can go and visit. And then I have meeting with administration with whatever programs we’re working on. In the afternoon I touch base with my VR and LEGO people. We’ll talk about expectations they might see, goals they might have, then they’ll go and see those people (patients). They usually touch base with me again at the end of the day or send me emails to provide me information. 
  11. [JJ] Then I spend the second half of my day with conversations likes this, or writing grants, or following up on projects that are currently running through the hospital. 
  12. [JJ] In my old role it was kind of mixed bag. I spent half the day working with patients going bedside with them, introducing new technologies to them. Once i started teaming up with gamestart school, which is a school that we contract with where Nate Aschenbach, who now works for ZOTT or gamechangers, I’m not sure which one, but he founded that. We worked very closely, first to get his people first volunteering, and then contracted to come in teach kids bedside gaming. When I started with them a lot of what I was doing was going and prepping kids for volunteers to come work with them. I go run ahead and let them know ‘hey these people are coming would you be interested in working with them, what are you likes/dislikes’, then when his volunteers would come the kids would be ready to go. They would teach them how to make video games. 
  13. [JJ] And the second half of my day was usually spent trying to coordinate all of that stuff. Figuring out what patients I’d be seeing the next day. Figuring out what groups I wanted to reach out or contact to. Also a lot of what we did was creating content with patients and the groups that were there. By creating content - I mean I would be filming interactions with the patients or groups so that we could share it through presentations within the hospital so we could better educate people about what we’re doing. But also at conferences and even on YouTube like hospital channels - daily and national new channels so we could educate the world with what it is we’re trying to do here at the hospital.
  14. [GD] Now we’re going to go into ZOTT. Do you use it and to what extent?
  15. [A] Personally I don’t use it that much because of the nature of my role. I do checkin and look at it. I have an IPAD with ZOTT on it. I look at it to see what they’re adding to it. As far as how we use it at our hospitals - When it was first introduced to me it was under the name GameChanger TV it was mid summer or early fall when we started using it. Initially the way we using it I had  - we didn’t have any devices dedicated to it. The hope was that we’d be able to run it on our TV and kids would just be able to watch it. Some of it worked on the TV and but some of it didn’t. But when it did work and it was streaming well we noticed that kids in the playroom really enjoyed kind of participating in that. We only had a couple events where that actually happened. Otherwise what we were doing was telling patients ‘you can access this from any device you have’ I had an intern at the time and his role was playing videogames with the kids and tell them about ZOTT. He’d do that and show them how to set it on on their phone, this was probably from sept to nov when this was happening. So that was the extent with how we were involved with ZOTT. Then in november/december Nate and Taylor ccame in and saw how we were working with it wasn’t working very well. we wern’t getting people interested, it was complicated for them to use their phones. It didn’t work well on all of the devices. but it worked well on IOS. So they doncated 9 ios devices to us. that currently ZOTT is overseeing. using a device management tool. so they push apps to it and update from where they are. And having those devices I was able to get childlfe more onboard. So right now we’re doing a pilot program on our 7th floor where we have a locker with the IPADs in them, it is up to our child life CLS and activity therapists to determine patients who they feel the ipads would be appropriate for - those are usually patients who are long term patients who have an interest in game or technology or youtube or anything like that. and they don’t have their own devices. If they have their own device they’ll just show them how to do it  through the ZOTT website. If they don’t have their own device they’ll give them an ipad. They’ll show them how to use it, but then we just leave it to them. 
  16. [A] What we’ve found so far is that they’ll look at ZOTT for a little bit they’ll usually just play the games that are on pre downloaded on the IPAD, then they wont check into ZOTT after that. Sometimes we’ll go over there and say ‘theres a streamer you might like’ and if we’re sitting next to them, then they’ll watch it, but they don’t take the initiatives after that. 
  17. [A] There was one patient and she was really excited - because she was spanish speaking and ZOTT had a spanish option  and so she really enjoyed that, and she utitlized it more than other patients. For the most part at this time its not getting used as much as I thought it would be or hope it would be.
  18. [GD] Are there any problems that technology staff are having?
  19. [A] The biggest part is that ZOTT is one more thing that they have to do, so making it as easy as possible for them. I think if they were able to access it through their television it would be a bit easier. Also there’s just not a lot on there that keeps the patients interest. I think if there were more traditional hollywood videos - I think that was one of the things that interested me at the very beginning when Jim came to me first talking about it. We have 40 video kids can choose from - limited- on our current system and they blow through those really fast. One of our biggest complaints is that they want more movies or they want to be able to watch their own movies like NETFLIX or HULU or things like that. One of the hopes when I was first being told about ZOTT was that it would have a pleathora of that - hoping that was really affordable or even free to our patients. And at the moments theres not that content - theres some sutff thats interesting to a niche group of kids. But theres not something that is appealing to a wider audience. 
  20. [A] One thing we’re still excited about and hoping to see is a safe way to use the stream so that we can deliver programming of our own to patients and families. But we don’t have a good method to providing that too them at the moment. And part of that is our own hospital system - our bandwidth just can’t handle live streams or live gaming, and so thats been a huge hurdle. Thats something ZOTT would help us with. They were talking about in the future they would have this solution for bandwidth issues - thats our biggest issue, we can’t do live streaming, and we can’t do live gaming because our hospitals bandwidth can’t handle it with the amount of patients we have here.  In the long run if we’re having everyone - one of the cool things with ZOTT is everybody can look and watch from any device. But if the bandwidth wont allow it then it wont work for us. 
  21. [GD] Does ZOTT compete with the device s the families bring in themselves.
  22. [JJ] SO families do have access - but one of our biggest patient disatisfiers right now is that when families try to do social gaming like online videogaming - they can’t . Our families can’t handle that with their own devices. When they try to watch netflix or hulu sometimes they can and sometimes the cant. Just depends on how many people are watching at once. (untelligible) Were telling everybody that could use all of their devices to do all of these things is its just going to clog up the bandwidth even more. Then we’re going to have people upset over not being able to watch the thing we promised they would watch. Thats a concern of ours and hoping ZOTT could have a solution for. 
  23. [GD] Do you know if other hospitals have similar bandwidth problems.
  24. [JJ] yes, I think bandwidth is a constant issue for many hospitals, some hospitals might be small and so less patients and having bandwidth may not be as big of an issue for them. We have 250 beds, we have thousands of people on this campus using internet all at one time and it cant handle it all the time. So our IT like to say we have the best internet int the country but theres just so many people in this one concentrated area
  25. [GD] Have you or your staff tried adding content into ZOTTs CMS
  26. [JJ] I have not yet. most (untelligible) for the amount of people are watching it at this time - its not worth the time for ne met me to do that. I have been thinking about doing that. I’ve been waiting to see whats in the next phase of ZOTT, and also we’re hoping to get a new upgrade that will expand our bandwidth so it will be more use friendly. So im hoping this summer to play around with it. we havent added anything. We have used stuff that other hs hospitals have put on there. 
  27. [JJ] What we’ve found so far is that we can view livestreams on our devices, but we definitely can view it on our TVs which have internet capability. We can livestream from our hospitals, we had patients live stream to twitch from our hospitals, and that was what kinda of got us excited about ZOTT - we had patients who were content creators. And one thing I’ve had patients who are content creators who create their own youTube channels or create their own artwork. Ive let ZOTT know about them and they’ve  contacted ZOTT and now their channel is a featured channel. Thats sometime Im really trying to take advantage of while working with them. M They really try to make the patient the c star
  28. [GD] I understand how zott can upload content globally into the platform. Have you ever had to edit or remove that content. change the visibility of any content
  29. [GGJJ} I have not, so far what they’ve put up there has been ok by uo our standards . I haven’t really messed around with that at all yet. 


  31. [GD] How often is that staff even touching ZOTT backend. It doesn’t sound like a lot
  32. [JJ] Never, no one has ever touched the backened. We’ve looked at it but we haven’t done anything with it yet.


  34. [GD] Have an any parents of the children who have used ZOTT said anything about the platform
  35. [JJ] the only one that sticks out are the parents of a child who had a child youtube channel. His content was actually featured on it. The parents were really excited about that, they thought it was really wonderful that there was a group out there acknowledging patient creation and highlighting that. And the parents of the child who was spanish speaking they were really excited to have something that was catered to them. A number of people have said they like that they could download games from ZOTT onto their phones. There were frustrations where it would say  ‘you could download games’ but when you go there like if you didn’t have the right devices for that game then it wouldn’t work. Some people saw that confusing and frustrating. But the ones who could download games were really excited to see that. 


  37. [GD] So the games you are talking about are the ones where you download through ZOTT but you play them outside of ZOTT?
  38. [JJ] Yeah, so ZOTT has this feature. They give you a free code that you can download it on your PC, or gaming device. If you have an IOS or android device, you can basically click on it and it will take you directly to the app store to download it. I found that to be a little misleading though, because a lot of those games are actually free games where the content was pay to play. To be honest at first I was excited and some of the games were fun and at the same time it was a little misleading I think because people throught they were getting this free game and what it was basically like you play the game, and every five minutes you hita. button and it wants you to pay something like that. It was one fo of those sticky situations where it says its free but its not really free


  40. [GD] How is ZOTT into introduced to patients?
  41. [JJ] So currently the way we do it is we, when we didnt have the devices, I had an intern going around introducing it. We educated the Child life staffa about it but they didnt think of it, or it was too complicated and too long to explain to a patient how to do it. But I had a dedicated intern who was shwo showing patients how to do it. and I also have my bedsite e bedside VR guy (andrew?) . If he saw a patient who was really - who he thought would click with it he would let them know. For a while he was introducing it to everyone he met but he found that it was getting a bit tedious, and a lot of e people would lose interest in his actual services that he was there to provide. Then he started letting kids know who showed an interest in like youtube channels or twitch or gaming. So he found that those are little more successful in getting kids interested in it. Currently the way that we’re doing it is that one floor that we’re piloting it it is up to our child live specialist or activity therapist to identify a patient who is in need the kind of services that ZOTT provides. And they provide them with an IPAD that has ZOTT on it - that was the easiest way to get staff on board. TO have a device and give it to them. At the same time its also a challenge for our staff because they have to keep track of the device, and they have to wipe the device after the patients done. So it comes with its own challenges. I remember way at the beginning of when were talking about using ZOTT JIM was talking about providing a device for every person in the hospital and that is a huge burden for our hospital. Its a very difficult process to try to do something like that. And some hospitals do it, but having just xbox 360s in every room I can tell you its not easy process. 


  43. [GD] If you had a magic wand what would you change about ZOTT.
  44. [JJ] My top thing is I would make it easily accessible on our big screen TVs. ANd i would make it have hollywood content , tons and tons of hollywood content. 


  46. [GD] So putting it on a big screen makes it a social experience?
  47. [JJ] It makes it more of a social experience, it a makes it so we dont have to keep track of tablets or patients have to explain t how to upload something on thier own tablet. And it makes it much more accessible to many patients. A lot of our patients are so sick or so debilitated that they cant actually handle a device on their own. But when he turns the tv on for them they can watch it on our big (unintelligible). So while I love the capability that it could be accessed on any device, I think thats a huge step above a lot of other things. I still think we need to be able to access it on our regular tvs and interact with it on a regular TV
  48. CLOSING END
